A woman enters the China Banking Regulatory Commission building in Beijing on May 20. Photo: VCGA woman who used to work at the China Banking Regulatory Commission (CBRC) has been sentenced to one year in jail for leaking confidential documents, showed court records.The Hengshui Intermediate People's Court in North China's Hebei Province released a judgment on the China Judgments Online website on Monday that the convicted, surnamed Li, 33, disclosed the guidance and draft explanation on regulating the assets of financial institutions during her temporary deployment at CBRC.According to the judgment, Li took 36 photos of the documents, which were still under internal consultation, and sent them to one of her former colleagues through social media on February 17, 2017, resulting in a wide range of leaks on the internet.Li had already received confidential training when she was seconded to the CBRC, and had been fully aware that the first page of the documents was written with the word "confidential" before she sent them out, said the judgment.China's National Administration of States Secret Protection has confirmed that the contents of the guidance and draft explanation are state secrets.Â Disclosure of such documents might cause serious damage, such as disrupting the financial deployment, undermining normal operations of state organs, and affecting the effectiveness of policy implementation, to the security of financial markets.The court said that Li's behavior constituted a crime of deliberate disclosure of state secrets and should be punished according to law.After the sentence, Li had no objection.Global Times Chinese scientists design gene-editing tool using light to kill cancer cellsAbsence at PLA maritime parade will prevent US from learning about Chinese Navy: expertsChinese American organization condemns increasing racial profiling in US Delegation of HUST attends alumni gala in Los AngelesChinese driving Vegas growthHaving fun